Chapter 1
Cohren
0430 Itania-Time. Cohren hated getting up so early. He hated it above all because he was responsible for waking up everyone else in his company. Quietly, he stood up from his bunk, put on his combat uniform, threw on his bulletproof vest, and took his things out of his locker, being careful with a certain small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. Everything he needed, like his oxygen mask or his special glasses, hung from it. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly left the barracks. Outside, mud and ice crunched under his boots.
He pulled out a lighter from one jacket pocket and a cigarette from the other. He lit it and took a short drag before opening the door a bit. In the past week, he had to come up with all sorts of things to wake up the men and women under his command. He no longer used the preset wake-up alarm because it usually didn't work and only a faint humming came from the speakers.
“Wake them up?” Cohren turned around and saw Zugführer Nemic approaching him.
"Yes", Cohren replied.
"What do you want to try this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and a few others came towards him already fully dressed.
"Good morning," said Craith.
"What woke you up, then?" asked Cohren.
"So, first of all, we didn't want to wait and see what you're going to come up with again today. And secondly, the shock troops, who get up first, can choose their morning ration," replied one of the men, Ravik. "And you know how bad the food can be."
"Good point, sergeant," said Cohren. He reached in and pressed a button. A loud, shrill alarm sounded in the barracks. Inside, he heard gentle cursing and people running around in confusion.
"Man, Valturi," said Nemic. "One would think they've learned by now to wake up at the same time as you."
"Well, my people from the training camp have learned," Cohren replied, pointing at Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "However, the platoon and squad leaders also know that they need to get up before their units."
Seconds later, the rest of the company came out. They had everything they needed, from personal items to necessary equipment. Some of the newer recruits looked confused, while others seemed annoyed.
"Good morning," said Cohren with a good mood.
"With all due respect, Sir, why do you have to wake us up like this?", asked a sergeant of the Shock Troops.
"Because regular alarms are crap and Daybreak doesn't sleep," said Cohren.
"Pack all your personal belongings," Cohren continued. As a lieutenant colonel and the executing officer of the company, he was responsible for supervising and supporting it together with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We're not coming back here. Sergeants and lieutenants, you and your squads have 15 minutes for the final checks and to pack the daily rations."
The members of the Exodus Company scattered quickly. They were part of the second Shock Troop Division, second army. Before they were merged, they were two companies, Cohort and Dagger. The company was split, and this was the main reason why Cohren had mixed feelings about his promotion to lieutenant colonel.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first unit, walked side by side under the glow of many generator-powered lamps at the forward deployment base. Most of them had red-tinted glass to avoid being detected by enemy bombers. Daybreak had fallen back on Wild Weasel attacks from the air and ground to counter them.
“A new day and a new task for the Hellhounds,” Nemic said with a dry laugh. “Where are they sending us?”
“A forward deployment base outside of Ianlos. We will support the ground attack,” Cohren replied and pulled on his cigarette. He gave Craith a partial blame for starting to smoke, but a year in service changed one, so he said nothing.
“Shit. It's getting worse at the front,” Nemic muttered. “All the news says: 'Support the war efforts. Send help to the Kurgan Front.' How about sending help to the Howland Front?”
“Amen, brother,” Cohren said and flicked the remains of his cigarette into the mud. “At least we're starting off with the first armed unit and don't have to run. Captain Shaw should already be there.”
“Shaw has given us a ride?” asked Nemic a bit surprised.
“Yes. He's not as bad as I thought, to be honest. Not very approachable, but you can manage with him.”
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his laryngectomy microphone and put on his backpack at the same time. “All units of the Exodus Company meet at the Fuhrpark West, once they are ready. We depart with the first armed unit at 0500.”
In the second-by-second response from the squad leaders, Haris, Craith, and Ravik, all of whom were non-commissioned officers of low rank when they came here, Cohren had the feeling that he had known them for an eternity, although it had been no more than two years. They were squad leaders, however, Craith had been leading the second unit for a week, since the previous unit leader had been discharged for medical reasons after being shot by a Daybreak sniper.
On the way to the Fuhrpark, Cohren and Nemic noticed a group of about eight Kronos combat tanks and four scout tanks. Their crew was hurrying around to make sure their machines were ready for action. Quickly, Cohren spotted Captain Boradin Shaw talking to the commander of the armed unit. As they approached, Shaw looked over at them and came over, as always with an expressionless face.
“Lieutenant Nemic… Lieutenant Valturi…“ He said, Cohren was slower, while he looked at Cohren's pistol holster and then looked up again. “The company is ready, I assume?”
